Scanned through the patch, quick comments

 - We need to implement our existing num-max-retries implementation as one of the policies
 - I think we should have the following API structure
{code}
message ApplicationSubmissionContext {
  ...
  ...
  // [default = max_retries_policy]
  optional ApplicationRetryPolicy app_retry_policy;
}

enum ApplicationRetryPolicyType {
  MAX_RETRIES_POLICY,
  WINDOWED_RETRIES_POLICY
}

message ApplicationRetryPolicy {
  // The following is really a required field
  optional ApplicationRetryPolicyType appRetryPolicyType [ default = MAX_RETRIES_POLICY ];

  // Only one of the following are accepted based on the type
  // Each is a context object specific to the policy type
  optional MaxApplicationRetriesPolicyContext;
  optional WindowedApplicationRetriesPolicyContext;
  ..
}

message MaxApplicationRetriesPolicyContext {
    optional int32 maxAppAttempts [default = 2];
}

message WindowedApplicationRetriesPolicyContext {
  optional int64 reset_time_window [default = 86400]
}
{code} 
 - Please don't add any setters/mutators in the read only interfaces like RMApp, RMAppAttempt. You can push them down to the implementations

Thinking if the following API is simpler to use. This is similar to the current patch, but flattens multiple protocol records into one protocol record. It's kind of adding one more dimension(reset-window) to the existing single dimension(maxAttempt) retry policy.
{code}
message ApplicationSubmissionContext {
  ...
  // [default = max_retries_policy]
  optional ApplicationRetryPolicy app_retry_policy;
}

message ApplicationRetryPolicy {
	optional int32 maxAppAttempts [default = 2]
	optional int64 reset_time_window [default = -1] # disable by default
}
{code}

[~xgong], the new patch looks good to me overall. I've just minor comments about the patch details.

1. failure account -> failure count?
{code}
+ *     when slidingWindowSize is set to > 0, the failure number will no take
+ *     failures which happen out of the window into failure account.
+ *     If failure account reaches to maxAppAttempts,
{code}

2. Make get/setSlidingWindowSize description more consistent?

3. EndTime -> FinishTime? The latter term seems to be more commonly used in YARN.

4. end_time violates the code convention.
{code}
+      long end_time = attempts.get(attemptIds.get(0)).getEndTime();
{code}

5. I think sort is not necessary. We can simply iterator over each attempt and check whether it should be take into account. The best sort is O(nlogn), though it doesn't make much difference, because there won't be too many attempts. Anyway, I think the additional sorting work seems not to be required.
{code}
+      Collections.sort(attemptIds, Collections.reverseOrder());
{code}

6. Why not using System.currentTimeMillis()?
{code}
+    setEndTime(Time.now());
{code}

7. In the test case, would you please add one more scenario: 2 failures within 6s will not restart the 3rd attempt.

One more missing comment above:

8. We should look back at the point when we make the decision based on the failure number, which means we should go back the time window from the current time instead of end_time.
{code}
+        if (attempt.getEndTime() >= end_time - this.slidingWindowSize) {
{code}

Almost good, just one minor thing:

1. You may want to mark this method \@Stable because the setter/getter is marked \@Stable.
{code}
+  @Unstable
+  public static ApplicationSubmissionContext newInstance(
{code}

